---

Scope of the Reference Implementation

This release includes:

signal inputs
structural decision resolution logic
rule evaluation and governance handling
demo application (Python)
outputs and reference outputs
validation traces

ORL-AI defines a deterministic decision model where decisions emerge from structure:

resolve(normalize(structure)) →

RESOLVED     if a valid unique decision exists
INCOMPLETE   if required signals are missing
ABSTAIN      if structure is conflicting or ambiguous

Ambiguity is defined as multiple incompatible decisions, not multiple matching rules.

---

What This Demonstrates

• decision resolution from fragmented signals
• independence from input ordering
• independence from timestamps and synchronized clocks
• safe handling of incomplete decision states
• conflict and ambiguity containment
• deterministic convergence across independent nodes
• reproducible decision outcomes

---

Conformance

An implementation is considered compatible if it preserves:

resolution based on normalized structure
independence from order as authority
independence from synchronized time
deterministic convergence
reproducibility under equivalent inputs
explicit INCOMPLETE and ABSTAIN handling

Conformance is judged by observable behavior, not internal implementation.

No specific algorithm, model, or internal design is mandated.

---

Relationship to Shunyaya Framework

ORL-AI is part of the broader Shunyaya Structural Universal Mathematics (SSUM) framework.

It builds on:

STOCRS → structure-first computation
SSUM-Time → time independence
ORL → structural truth systems

